If all your infrastructure components (servers, containers, VPC, networking, etc.) show a healthy status but the application itself isn’t running, the issue usually lies at the application layer rather than the underlying resources. Here’s how you can systematically narrow it down:

🔍 Common Causes
Startup/Deployment Errors

Application code has bugs or missing dependencies.

Incorrect build artifacts (e.g., wrong JAR/WAR in Java, missing Docker image layers).

Configuration Issues

Environment variables not set (DB credentials, API keys).

Misconfigured ports (app listening on 8080 but load balancer expects 80).

Service Dependencies

Database or external API reachable but authentication failing.

DNS resolution errors for dependent services.

Permissions

IAM roles or service accounts missing required access.

File system permissions blocking app startup.

Runtime Errors

Out-of-memory (OOMKilled in containers).

Thread deadlocks or unhandled exceptions.

🛠️ How to Overcome It
Check Application Logs

Look at container logs (docker logs <container>), EC2 logs, or CloudWatch logs.

Identify if the app is crashing, stuck, or failing to bind to a port.

Verify Configuration

Ensure environment variables, secrets, and config files are correctly loaded.

Double-check port mappings between app, container, and load balancer.

Test Dependencies

Run connectivity checks (telnet, curl, ping) to DBs or APIs.

Validate credentials and permissions.

Resource Monitoring

Check CPU/memory usage. If OOM errors occur, increase resources or optimize code.

Health Checks

Confirm that the app’s health endpoint (/health, /status) is correctly implemented and returning 200.

Rollback/Restart

If a new deployment caused the issue, roll back to the last working version.

Restart the app/service to clear transient errors.

👉 In short: infra being healthy doesn’t guarantee app health. The fix almost always comes from logs + configs + dependency checks.


🧭 App Not Running but Infra Healthy — Checklist
1. Start Troubleshooting
Confirm infra components (EC2, ECS, EKS, DB, Load Balancer) show “Healthy.”

Move focus to application layer.

2. Check Application Logs
Inspect logs for startup errors, missing dependencies, or exceptions.

If errors found → fix and redeploy.

If no errors → proceed to configuration checks.

3. Verify Configurations
Ensure environment variables are correctly set.

Check port mappings (app vs. container vs. load balancer).

Validate config files and secrets.

4. Test Dependencies
Run connectivity tests to DBs, APIs, or external services.

Confirm credentials and IAM permissions.

If dependencies fail → fix access or credentials.

5. Monitor Resources
Check CPU/memory utilization.

If OOMKilled or throttled → increase resources or optimize code.

6. Health Checks
Verify /health or /status endpoint returns 200.

If failing → restart or rollback deployment.

7. Final Validation
Recheck app status.

If still not running → revisit configuration or dependency layer.

✅ Outcome
App running successfully → mark issue as resolved.